<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,487,712]" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">
<bibRefCitation box="[151,376,487,512]" pageId="2" pageNumber="473" refString="Cesar, J., Bouyer, J., Granjon, L., Akoudjin, M., Guerrini, L. &amp; Louppe, D. (2010) Les relictes forestieres de la falaise de Banfora: un peuplement original au voisinage de Bobo-Dioulasso, Burkina Faso. Bois et Forets des Tropiques, 305 (3), 43 - 55." type="journal article">
César 
<emphasis box="[227,281,487,512]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">et al</emphasis>
. (2010)
</bibRefCitation>
illustrate the caterpillar in dorsal view on 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sprague" authorityYear="1909" box="[896,1173,487,512]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malpighiaceae" genus="Acridocarpus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="2" pageNumber="473" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="chevalieri">
<emphasis box="[896,1173,487,512]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">Acridocarpus chevalieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[1192,1360,487,512]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malpighiaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="2" pageNumber="473" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Malpighiaceae</taxonomicName>
) from riverine gallery forest, Burkino Faso. Jérémy Bouyer, who took that image, shared this and additional images (
<figureCitation box="[158,253,554,579]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1826,1848]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,447,1801]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,447,1801]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Final instar caterpillar of Pyrrhiades aeschylus, photographed on Acridocarpus chevalieri, riverine gallery forest, Dafra, Burkino Faso, 1 Jun 2007, by Jérémy Bouyer. 1, view of head at basal end of leaf shelter; 2, view of posterior region at distal end of leaf shelter; 3, detail of head anterodorsal view; 4, caterpillar, dorsal view. (© J. Bouyer)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/855775/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="473">Figure 1</figureCitation>
). It can be seen that the final instar caterpillar rests in a simple leaf roll shelter, with its head visible at the basal end (Figure 1.1) and the posterior segments visible at the distal end (Figure 1.2). Comparing the images with the description by 
<bibRefCitation author="Fleury" box="[371,530,621,646]" pageId="2" pageNumber="473" refString="Fleury, P. de (1926) Etudes sur la faune lepidopterologique de la Guinee francaise. Annales de la Societe entomologique de France, 95, 131 - 155." type="journal article" year="1926">Fleury (1926)</bibRefCitation>
(repeated in 
<bibRefCitation author="Cock" box="[689,833,621,646]" pageId="2" pageNumber="473" refString="Cock, M. J. W. (2010 b) Observations on the biology of Afro - tropical Hesperiidae (Lepidoptera) principally from Kenya. Part 1." type="book" year="2010" yearSuffix="b">Cock 2010b</bibRefCitation>
), there is a close match, except that Fleury did not mention that the head is orange-red, with a row of four black spots across the upper face and another spot covering the stemmata.
</paragraph>
